title: For Sale:  Custom CZ-52 7.62x25 with Novak target sights and 7.62x25 ammo
postcontent:
PRICE DROP for quick sale. Will be put back in the safe after Friday if not sold. This fine single-action handgun was made in 1954 and imported in the early 90's (no import marks). Included are three magazines with aftermarket extended floorplates for fast reloads, the original holster, and the option to include 520 rounds of ammo. The CZ-52 is widely accepted to be a more robust design than the TT-33, utilizing the roller delayed-blowback action like the MG-42, HK G3, and MP5. The original rollers have been replaced with new hardened steel ones. The original firing pin has also been replaced with a hardened steel model that won't break when dry fired. The original tiny fixed sights were milled off and 1911 style Novak adjustable target sights installed- the difference is amazing compared to the factory sights. The original Bakelite grips were sealed and then painted black. The parkerized finish on the frame is in 90%+ original  condition and the slide has been coated in Dark Parkerizing Gray Alumahyde II rustproof gun coating (properly cured) so it can be carried IWB without worrying about rusting from sweat. Function wise, I have never had any malfunction in 500 rounds. The decocker/safety works properly and the hammer does not contact the firing pin when decocking.

It fires the potent 7.62x25mm tokarev round which will defeat both sides of a threat level IIa bullet proof vest or one side of a level II vest with normal target grade FMJ's. The now banned 320 (of 520) hardened steel core AP rounds I am including will defeat all soft body armor up to level III. These rounds are legal to own in all 50 states, they can just no longer be imported into the country or manufactured.

The gun has a very thin profile and can be concealed as easily and sometimes better than a 1911. If you're expecting bad guys with body armor and want better penetration than a .357 SIG, this is the gun for you. Would make a perfect glove box gun to shoot through glass and sheet metal if needed to. Hollow points are available online if you are concerned about over-penetration.

The ammo available is:
100 rounds of banned Norinco mild steel core non-corrosive FMJ
100 rounds of S&B indoor range safe new production non-corrosive reloadable FMJ
320 rounds of mixed Hintenberger and another European manufacture 1955 and 1962 production hardened steel core AP. The finest 7.62 ammo ever available to civilians, last available in 1990. This ammo is mildly corrosive like most surplus stuff. It is very clean brass cased and berdan primed. I have shot through 1/4" steel plate like it wasn't there, and I have seen it shred Kevlar helmets.

Besides defense, this is one heck of a fun gun to shoot. It sounds like a .44 magnum going off, and it has the recoil of a .45 1911. Minute of bad guy accuracy out to 150 yards from a bench, and very flat shooting. 9mm luger drop-in conversion barrels are available online.

I'm looking for a new toy, so this one has to go. 

$400 cash for the pistol and three mags and holster.
$600 cash OBO for the above plus all the ammo.

Ammo is not for sale without the gun.

The sights, modern steel upgrades, and magazines are worth $400 alone.

I am open to trades and trades plus cash for firearms and military related equipment, silver, cool stuff etc. What do you have? Worst I can say is no thanks. I am NOT interested in your used SCUBA gear, marijuana grow lights, or fish tanks.

If you are reading this, it's still for sale. 

Will meet at the Tulalip Cabelas in Marysville, WA only. Will ship overnight to your FFL at your expense for $50. Ammo ships separately for $20. 

I am a CPL holder and will only sell to US citizens 18 and older with valid ID and bill of sale. If you have a CPL or WAC card, no bill of sale is necessary.

Thank you for looking, and remember to vote no on I-594 this November.

Let's make a deal! Open to trades.

Up for sale is my Winchester model 77 semi-auto .22lr rifle. It grades in 95%+ condition, all parts matching and original. One factory magazine included. Bluing is perfect besides the normal wear line under the charging handle. A couple light scratches and one small ding in the walnut stock, but it's all storage wear. Very nice for a 50 year old rifle. Bore is mirror bright. the rifle functions flawlessly and it has never jammed on me. Zero rust, corrosion, or pitting.

Extremey accurate. Shoots sub-MOA at 100 yards with bulk ammo. This may also be because there are very rare Redfield micrometer adjustable target sights installed on the rifle. The very same used by the U.S. shooting team in the 1960's. These sights alone sell for $300 on Gunbroker. The receiver also has a rail so you could take the sights off and attach a scope if you wanted.

Also included are vintage Lyman sight inserts. Just unscrew a cap on the front sight and you can switch out the sight picture to a few different options including a red-orange filter. 

And I'm throwing in a sealed new production brick of Remington 22lr ammo to sweeten the deal. 

These quality Winchesters couldn't compete against the cheap Marlins and they were only produced for a few years even though they are one of the finest .22 rifles ever made. The milling and finish work is second to none, and the barrel is super-heavy compared to any of my other 22's.

title: For Sale:  Leupold VARI-X 2x7 Compact, gloss finish; duplex reticle.
postcontent:
Leupold VARI-X 2x7 Compact, gloss finish; duplex reticle.

Looks new, no scratches or wear anywhere, Center fire  Rifle model.

Comes with Leupold Golden RingÂ® Full Lifetime Guarantee

If any Leupold Golden RingÂ® product is found to have defects in materials or workmanship, Leupold & Stevens, Inc. will repair, or if repair is not possible, either replace the product or refund the purchase price, whichever you prefer. FREE. Even if you are not the original owner. No warranty card is required. No time limit applies. 

All air to glass lens surfaces in the Vari-X 2-7x28mm Compact that is the subject of this review receive Leupold's standard magnesium fluoride anti-reflection coatings for enhanced light transmission and freedom from glare. It is built on a 1" diameter main tube made of 6061-T6 aircraft quality aluminum alloy and adjusted to be parallax free at a distance of 150 yards. The coin-slot windage and elevation adjustments are of the continuous friction type and are marked in 1/2 minute of angle increments. The eyepiece focus is by multiple turns of the ocular housing on fine threads and is secured with a knurled locking ring. Like all Leupold scopes, the 2-7x28 is sealed against moisture and nitrogen filled, making it waterproof and fog free.

The 2-7x28 Compact is shipped with Leupold's standard Duplex reticle. This type of reticle, with heavy a crosshair that becomes a fine crosshair near the center of the field, was invented by Leupold and has since been copied by virtually all other scope manufacturers. It is the best reticle ever designed for general purpose hunting applications. For the shooter who requires something different, the Leupold Custom Shop can install any of Leupold's 16 reticles (which include several specialized types not regularly available).

As its name implies, the 2-7 Compact was designed to be more compact than Leupold's regular 2-7x33mm variable power scope. It has a smaller front objective bell and is shorter and lighter than a standard 2-7 scope. This scope can be mounted low and overbore on most rifles, and will affect the handling and balance of the rifle less than a conventional scope. These are important advantages. Compact scopes are a natural match for today's lightweight, short action rifles.

There are two versions of the 2-7x28, one (intended for big game hunting) is adjusted to be parallax free at 150 yards, and the other (a Rimfire Special version) is adjusted to be parallax free at 60 yards and is supplied with a fine duplex reticle. They are otherwise identical.

The standard Vari-X 2-7x28 Compact reviewed here comes with a gloss black finish. It is 9.9 inches in length, and weighs only 8.2 ounces, making it one of the lightest 2-7x variables on the market. The 100 yard field of view is 41.7 feet at 2x and 16.5 feet at 7x. Optimum eye relief is 3.0-3.8 inches; the adjustment range is 80 MOA in both windage and elevation.

7.62x54R cartridges are packed in 15 round boxes or 20 round paper wrapped bundles. After the early 1960's stripper clips and the 15 round boxes were no longer used. 22- twenty round bundles (440 rounds) are packaged in a tin, two tins to a case. 18- fifteen round boxes (270 rounds) were packed in a tin marked with a "brackets" symbol denoting the inclusion of stripper clips. The transition from the early rectangular galvanized tins to painted tins with rounded corners occurred in the very early 1960's.
These were only made for 2 years 60 and 61 270rds of 147gr LPS with 54 surplus chargers can is unopened.
This ammo is EXTREMELY RARE ALMOST AS HARD TO FIND AS 7N1
